ngdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Weston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from any of numerous places called Weston, from Old English <i>west</i> ‘west’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’.","topographic name from Middle English <i>atte west tun(e)</i> ‘at the west farmstead, settlement’ (Old English <i>west</i> + <i>tūn</i>), or from Middle English <i>(bi) weste(n)tune</i> (Old English <i>be westan tūne</i> or <i>be west in tūne</i>), denoting someone who lived either to the west of a settlement or in the western part of a settlement. The latter was a common surname in Sussex."],"variants":[{"name":"Wesson","meanings":["English (Midlands and Kent): variant of   Weston  .","History: John Wesson came from England to Salem, MA, in 1644."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes de Weston was born in 1205, in Weston, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John De Weston, Magister, was 36 and her mother, Isolde de Newton, was 32. She had at least 1 son with Ralph Griffin, Snr."},"et":{"1205–":"1205–Surnud","1195–1258":"1195–1258","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1200–1284":"1200–1284","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1169–1227":"1169–1227","1173–Female":"1173–Surnud","1205":"1205","1227":"1227","1258":"1258","1169":"1169","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1284":"1284","1173":"1173","1195":"1195","Weston, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Weston, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1205–":"1205–Kuollut","1195–1258":"1195–1258","1205–Female":"1205–Kuollut","1200–1284":"1200–1284","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1169–1227":"1169–1227","1173–Female":"1173–Kuollut","1205":"1205","1227":"1227","1258":"1258","1169":"1169","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1284":"1284","1173":"1173","1195":"1195","Weston, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Weston, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1205–":"1205–Décédée","1195–1258":"1195–1258","1205–Female":"1205–Décédée","1200–1284":"1200–1284","1210–Male":"1210–Décédé","1169–1227":"1169–1227","1173–Female":"1173–Décédée","1205":"1205","1227":"1227","1258":"1258","1169":"1169","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1284":"1284","1173":"1173","1195":"1195","Weston, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Weston, Staffordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Agnes de Weston est née en 1205, à Weston, Staffordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni